The Economics of Violence
KOPENHAGEN – What is the largest source of violence in our world?
Brutal conflicts in Syria, in Ukraine and elsewhere are constantly in the news and therefore many would probably say war.
Yet this turns out to be a major mistake.
The correct answer plays a role when we want to find cost-effective solutions for this and other global problems.
It goes without saying that everyone would like to end war and violence, just as we would like to end poverty, hunger and global warming and provide everyone with access to education.
However, given limited resources, there are limits to what the international community can do.
We must set priorities, and for this one can use an economic cost-benefit analysis.
The international community is working on new development goals for the next 15 years, and the Copenhagen Consensus has asked some of the world's leading economists to assess which goals, in their view, would be the wisest.
Is the goal of reducing violence worth the use of resources that would otherwise, for example, be used to combat hunger?
And, if so, which forms of violence should be targeted?
According to a study by James Fearon from Stanford University and Anke Höffler from the Center for the Study of African Economies at Oxford University, violence in society – murders and especially violence against women and children – presents a far greater problem than civil wars.
For every death on the battlefield of a civil war, nine people die as a result of interpersonal violence, and for every two combatants who die, one child is killed.
In 2008, 418,000 people were killed worldwide, and too many countries report murder rates exceeding 10 victims per 100,000 inhabitants, which the World Health Organization describes as an epidemic.
A single murder in America costs a person's life and society 9.1 million US dollars.
Gemessen am Nationalkommen weltweit kostet allein diese Form von Gewaltverbrechen 1,7% des globalen Bruttosozialprodukts (BIP).
Natürlich handelt es sich dabei nicht um einen direkten finanziellen Verlust für die Weltwirtschaft, sondern um eine Art und Weise, die Folgen zum Ausdruck zu bringen.
Wenn Morde abgeschafft werden könnten, wären Gesellschaften auf aller Welt in einer Weise besser gestellt, die sich mit 1,7% des BIP beziffern lässt.
Vergleichen wir dies mit den deutlich geringen Kosten von Bürgerkriegen, die rund 0,2% des weltweiten BIP entsprechen.
Das ist allerdings immer noch viel weniger als die größte Quelle von Gewalt überhaupt: häusliche Gewalt gegen Frauen.
Based on studies published in the scientific journal Science, 28% of all women in Africa south of the Sahara experienced violence from their intimate partners or family members last year.
This includes women who were beaten, forced into early marriage, exposed to sexual violence, victims of crimes in the name of "honor," and subjected to female genital mutilation.
According to a cautious estimate, the societal costs of violence by intimate partners alone amount to 4.4 trillion US dollars or 5.2% of the global GDP.
The second-largest source of violence is child abuse, which is committed by parents in 80% of cases.
The definition of what constitutes child abuse varies across cultures, but roughly 15% of children suffer each month what the UN refers to as severe physical punishment.
Hierzu zählen Schläge ins Gesicht, an den Kopf oder auf die Ohren, und ein Viertel dieser Kinder wird wiederholt und so heftig wie möglich mit einem Gegenstand geschlagen.
Jeden Monat ergeht dieses Leid über rund 290 Millionen Kinder.
Die sozialen Kosten belaufen sich auf 3,6 Billionen US-Dollar oder 4,2% des globalen BIP.
Ein winziger Bruchteil der internationalen Hilfsgelder fließt derzeit in die Verringerung von Gewalt in der Gesellschaft und in die Verbesserung von Strafrechtssystemen.
Die enormen Kosten, die von der Gesellschaft und von Einzelnen getragen werden, schreien förmlich danach, etwas zu unternehmen.
Unfortunately, there are still very few secure insights into where the limited resources should best be applied.
All that can be said is that the money spent to reduce violence could be used more targetedly.
Large sums of aid money are intended for "fragile states" to help end or prevent civil wars, yet only 0.27% of international aid goes to projects with the "crime prevention" component.
Other programs may contribute indirectly, but it is obvious that much could be done better.
Some solutions, as much is clear, work very well.
More capable social institutions can reduce child abuse.
Studies in the US state of Washington have shown that home visits by trained staff can reduce child abuse, improve children's quality of life and their physical and mental health, and reduce the costs of care and legal proceedings.
A dollar spent on this program produces a benefit worth $14: it is therefore an extremely cost-effective measure.
In many cases, societal attitudes must change.
To reduce violence against women and girls, a program named SASA! in Uganda is working on this.
(Kisuaheli für „Jetzt!“) dafür ein, die Auffassung zu verbreiten, dass Gewalt in der Partnerschaft inakzeptabel ist und hat dazu beigetragen, die Zahl der Fälle zu halbieren.
Das ist ein fantastisches Resultat, auch wenn dazu keine Analyse der Kosteneffizienz vorliegt.
Es gibt Beispiele aus anderen Ländern, in denen wirksame Maßnahmen ergriffen werden.
Im Jahr 1993 hat es in Bogotá 80 Morde auf je 100.000 Einwohner gegeben.
Mit einem umfassenden Ansatz – eine zeitliche Begrenzung für den Verkauf von Alkohol, die Rückeroberung des öffentlichen Raumes und Verbesserungen im Polizei- und Justizsystem – wurde die Mordrate auf 21 Opfer je 100.000 Einwohner im Jahr 2004 gesenkt.
That is still a high number, but significantly lower than the murder rate of 55 victims per 100,000 residents in Detroit.
Alcohol plays a role in many violent attacks, and insights from Bogotá suggest that controlling its availability could be of significant importance.
In the United Kingdom, a pilot study on better enforcement of existing regulations showed that violent attacks could be reduced in a very cost-effective manner, with the benefits outweighing the costs by a ratio of 17 to 1.
We still do not know enough, but two points are clear: First, domestic violence against women and children brings costs to society of $8 billion per year and thus represents a massive – and far too little noticed – global problem.
Secondly, there are solutions that can help address some of these problems in a very cost-effective manner.
Aus diesem Grund gehört die Verringerung häuslicher Gewalt in die engere Auswahl für die nächsten Entwicklungsziele der Welt.
